    "summary": "The Battle of Crécy (August 26, 1346 AD) was the first major English land victory of the [[event:2235|Hundred Years' War]], in which Edward III's army — including a powerful force of English and Welsh longbowmen — decisively defeated a much larger French army of knights and Genoese crossbowmen in northern France, demonstrating that the longbow could shatter the most expensive military force of the age: the mounted armored knight. The battle was emblematic of the late medieval military revolution in which disciplined missile infantry superseded the aristocratic cavalry charge as the dominant battlefield force.\n\nThe French army's Genoese crossbow mercenaries opened the battle but were rapidly overwhelmed by the faster-firing English longbowmen, who could loose twelve arrows per minute compared to the crossbow's two. When the Genoese retreated, French knights charged them down in frustration, creating disorder before advancing against the English position. The English longbow volleys brought down horses, killing or disabling the riders under the weight of their armor; French cavalry charged the English line at least fifteen times and were repulsed each time. King Philip VI of France fled. The battle reportedly killed between 1,500 and 4,000 French nobles and knights — an aristocratic bloodletting of the first order. Crécy also saw the first confirmed use of cannon in a major Western European land battle, though the bombards were more psychological than militarily decisive. The victory enabled Edward III's subsequent siege and capture of Calais (1347), which England held for over two centuries.",
    "wikipedia_url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Battle_of_Cr%C3%A9cy",
